N.Y. / Region

Q&A: Irwin D. Simon; A Dynamo in the Food Marketing Arena

By STEWART AINAPRIL 12, 1998



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









SINCE he founded the Hain Food Group in Uniondale in 1993, Irwin D. Simon has guided the concern from that of a small natural and specialty food consolidator to a marketer of more than 1,000 niche food products under 11 brand names.Mr. Simon, the company's president and chief executive officer, received the Entrepreneur of the Year award last year from Ernst & Young after increasing the company's sales from $2 million in 1993 to $65 million last year. The son of a local retail-store owner, Mr. Simon was born in Glace Bay, Canada. His first job in 1982 was as assistant product manager of William Neilsen Ltd. in Toronto, a large food conglomerate, where he worked on the Haagen-Dazs ice cream account. In 1985, Pillsbury bought Haagen-Dazs and recruited him to work for it in New York, where he stayed until 1991 working in sales, marketing, business development and retail shops. For the next year-and-a-half, Simon worked as vice president of sales and marketing for Slim-Fast Foods. He then started his own company. He is married and has one child.Q.  Why did you start your own business?A.  I had a vision of wanting to buy companies with niche brands and niche categories. A lot of people talk about it, a lot of people want to do it, and there are some who do it.Q.  Why?A.  Because I saw nobody doing it. I saw nobody taking kosher foods, medically directed foods, health foods, to the next level. When we acquired Kineret, the packaging was 18th-century packaging. When I went to them and said we have to do low-fat and better-for-you foods, they said nobody would eat them.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Q.  The people at Kineret didn't believe it.A.  They didn't and they didn't believe in spending money on advertising, packaging or anything like that. My philosophy was that if I bought a lot of small companies and brought the lessons I learned in corporate America, my strategic vision and the entrepreneurealship that I had growing up as a kid and being in a family business, that I could take all these little businesses to the next level. They had not shown up on the screen of the big guys yet; the big guys were not there. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Q.  They didn't have these products?A.  Right, there was no big multi-food company in the kosher food business, the natural food business, the medically directed food business. And so I felt I couldn't get stomped on because there was no one there.Q.  And what was the vision you said you had?A.  My vision was making foods that taste good, that were healthier types of food -- whether they were low in fat, lower in saturated fat, lower in sodium, foods for diabetics, foods for people who kept kosher, foods that only had natural ingredients.Q.  And now products must contain a label with a listing of ingredients.A.  That's what really set me apart. In 1994, the nutritional labeling laws came into effect and everything became standardized. That went in my favor because now people knew the percentage of saturated fat and how much sodium there was in there. Someone could call a product healthy, but what were the calories? We tell people, ''Read our labels, read our ingredients.'' We're proud of what's in it. So I wanted to build brands and provide foods that were better for you.Q.  What else was important?A.  I didn't want to be a manufacturer or own brick and mortar and build plants and stuff like that. I like to keep things simple in my life and if I could concentrate on building a brand and let someone else manufacture these products for me under my formulas and recipes -- and I had strict quality assurance in place -- that was my strategy. All the money I ever saved I put into this business.Q.  Did you borrow as well?A.  I mortgaged my apartment and my wife is still working. I took a big risk because I walked away from a six-figure job. I had no income and put my life on hold. I was married two or three years and didn't want to have children because I had no income. And the more people told me I was crazy, that it wouldn't work, the harder I worked.Q.  Why did people think you were crazy? What you were doing is called food consolidation, right?A.  Well, nobody ever really did it in the better-for-you category -- in healthier foods. I was the first. And I was trying to do it with not a lot of money.
