Q.  How did you go about it?A.  In my first year I bought four little companies -- Kineret, Farm Foods, Pizsoy and California Slim. And I tried to take all of these four and merge them together. Why? So they would have enough cash flow to pay some of the bills. And people said that most people have trouble doing one acquisition, you'll never be able to pull four off. So, throughout the year, I can't tell you how many times a deal was almost dead or how many times a bank slammed the door in my face as I tried to find the financing to acquire the companies. I had deals with every one of them to go ahead and acquire them, and I gave them money out of my own pocket that I would have lost if I couldn't get the necessary financing.Q.  So how did you finally pull it off?A.  I found a small underwriter on Long Island, Lew Liberbaum, who took me public and raised me $4 million. We went public in November 1993 and after I paid off my debts, I had $350,000 left. So I knew I had to do something bigger. A week after I closed on my initial public offering, Pet, a large conglomerate, was selling the Hain Hollywood division, a $50 million division. I flew to St. Louis to negotiate this deal with a letter from one of my investment banker friends that said I could raise $21 million. And I won the bid and then went out and raised $21 million. So in April 1994 I acquired Hain Hollywood.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Q.  How did you manage all of this?A.  I had no infrastructure and Hain was a business in St. Louis with a product line. I operated out of the back of the Kineret warehouse in Jericho.Q.  When did you move to Uniondale?A.  In August '94. And in our first year of owning Hain, we paid back $12 million of our debt. In November '95, we bought Estee from a large German company by again going out and borrowing the money.Q.  And you bought the licensing rights to Weight Watchers Gourmet Foods in March 1997. So where do you see your future growth -- in acquisitions or through the purchase of more licensing rights?A.  The No. 1 way we grow is through new products and new distribution. Estee is a food product line for the diabetic. As you know, drug stores sell a lot of food and the No. 3 perscription sold in a drugstore today is insulin. But Estee is not in drugstores yet, so we have a big opportunity with drugstores. We also have a big opportunity to expand Hains, Weight Watchers and others. Acquisitions are a big part of our growth. We're looking at acquisitions all the time and want to grow more through acquisitions than strategic alliances. Weight Watchers is a great product line for us, but we don't own the brand. We want to own our brands. We want to be a property owner, not a property manager.Q.  A big part of your growth will be with organic foods.A.  Yes. Over 60 percent of our Westbrae products are organic, and 10 or 12 percent of Hain products are organic. So we see a big growth in organic products, diabetic products, weight management products and kosher products.Q.  What did you learn from your days with big companies?A.  To be expedient in doing things. We came out with 60 new products in one year with Hain. When I worked in the big companies, it would take us seven years to come out with 60 new products. So strategic marketing, being a visionary and making things happen quickly all came from big company experience.Q.  In the future, I understand you are looking at breakfast foods and baby products.A.  Our company's natural foods today control six of the top 15 categories. We want to introduce a lot of prepared meals for kids, and we're working on some prepared breakfast-type products. We'd like to go into baby food if we could find the right strategic acquisition. What we want to do is introduce babies to organic or healthy food first, and you bring new users into baby foods every nine months. What we want to do then is introduce them into Hain kids products. I have a 2 1/2-year-old daughter, and we have animal crackers in which there are no artificial colors, flavors or preservatives. And there is not a lot of sugar in this, and it's great for kids.Q.  Do you want your products in health food stores or supermarkets?A.  Both. The natural food stores are great stores. Supermarkets today are also putting natural foods or better-for-you sections within their store, and we want to be located in that section of the store. I do not want my cookies in with Keebler or Nabisco cookies, I want them in the natural food or better-for-you aisle. When you are in specialty foods, people are brand loyal. When you mention a frozen challah, the first thing that comes to your mind is Kineret. Continue reading the main story






